09040nam a22009855i 9783110473780DE-B159720210202111235.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210202t20162015pl     fo  d z      eng d  a2016498793  a(OCoLC)980193241  a97831104737807 a10.1515/97831104737802doi  a(DE-B1597)463775  a(OCoLC)979751242  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aplcPL 7aPSY0030002bisacsh1 aRiva, Giuseppe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Psychology of Social Networking Vol.1 :bPersonal Experience in Online Communities /cGiuseppe Riva, Brenda K. Wiederhold, Pietro Cipresso. 1aWarsaw ;aBerlin : bDe Gruyter Open Poland, c[2016] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Contributing Authors -- tIntroduction -- t1. Psychology Of Social Media: From Technology To Identity -- t2. Peer and Professional Online Support for Parents -- t3. Online Counseling for Migrant Workers: Challenges and Opportunities -- t4. Using Facebook: Good for Friendship But Not So Good for Intimate Relationships -- t5. Communicatively Integrated Model of Online Community: A Conceptual Framework and Empirical Validation on a Case of a Health- Related Online Community -- t6. Effects of Network Connections on Deception and Halo Effects in Linkedin -- t7. The Dark Side of Social Networking Sites in Romantic Relationships -- t8. Making and Keeping the Connection: Improving Consumer Attitudes and Engagement in E-Mental Health Interventions -- t9. Intersubjectivity in Video Interview -- t10. Ethical and Regulatory Considerations For Social Media Research -- t11. Media Theories and the Facebook Influence Model -- t12. Social Networking and Romantic Relationships: A Review of Jealousy and Related Emotions -- t13. What is Lurking? A Literature Review of Research on Lurking -- t14. Can Social Media Photos Influence College Students' Sexual Health Behaviors? -- t15. Social Networks as a Communication Tool from Children's Perpective: A Twitter Experience -- t16. The Influence of Extraversion on Individuals' SNS Use -- tList of Figures -- tList of Tables0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aUsing a novel approach to consider the available literature and research, this book focuses on the psychology of social media based on the assumption that the experience of being in a social media has an impact on both our identity and social relationships. In order to 'be online', an individual has to create an online presence - they have to share information about themselves online. This online self is presented in different ways, with diverse goals and aims in order to engage in different social media activities and to achieve desired outcomes. Whilst this may not be a real physical presence, that physicality is becoming increasingly replicated through photos, video, and ever-evolving ways of defining and describing the self online. Moreover, individuals are using both PC-based and mobile-based social media as well as increasingly making use of photo and video editing tools to carefully craft and manipulate their online self. This book therefore explores current debates in Cyberpsychology, drawing on the most up-to-date theories and research to explore four main aspects of the social media experience (communication, identity, presence and relationships). In doing so, it considers the interplay of different areas of psychological research with current technological and security insight into how individuals create, manipulate and maintain their online identity and relationships. The social media are therefore at the core of every chapter, with the common thread throughout being the very unique approach to considering diverse and varied online behaviours that may not have been thus far considered from this perspective. It covers a broad range of both positive and negative behaviours that have now become integrated into the daily lives of many westernised country's Internet users, giving it an appeal to both scholarly and industry readers alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified individually in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Applied Psychology.2bisacsh  aBehavior.  aMedia Modeling.  aMedia psychology.  aSNSs.  aSocial Networking.1 aJordan, Alexander H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTuliao, Antover P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlianan, Arsenio S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClough, Bonnie A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWiederhold, Brenda K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNieuwboer, C.C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCipresso, Pietro, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDiekema, Doug, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRiva, Giuseppe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetrič, Gregor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOdabasi, H. Ferhan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChou, Hui-Tzu Grace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuillory, Jamie E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHancock, Jeffrey T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov